def GenPlot(df, save_plot, out_ti,  fext, start, stop):
    """
    Parameters:
        * df = dataframe of DU material class
        * TITLE = text plot title
        * out_ti = figure title
        * save _plot = save the plot 'Y' or 'N'
        * fext = output file extension (eg '.png')
        * start = earliest date in data set (round it to the nearest century)
        * stop latest date in the dataset (round it to nearest century)
    Requires: seaborn, matplotlib.pyplot and numpy
    """
    import  matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import matplotlib.patches as mpatches
    import seaborn as sns
    import numpy as np


    df['lbl'] = df.DU +'-'+ df.Cat.fillna(df.mcls)

    x2 = df

    my_range = range(1, len(x2.index)+1)

    x_ticks = []
    for i in range(start, stop, 100):
        x_ticks.append(i)

    # Plot style
    if len(x2) > 15:
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    else:
        pass

    if len(x2) > 20:
        plt.yticks(my_range, x2.lbl, fontsize=12)
    else:
       
        plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 11)


    sns.set_style("white", rc= {"xtick.bottom": True, "ytick.left": True,})
    sns.set_context("paper", font_scale = 0.9)
    plt.hlines(y=my_range, xmin=x2['date3'], xmax=x2['date4'], color='black', alpha= 1)
    plt.scatter(x2['date3'], my_range, color='black', alpha= 1, label='date3', s = 11)


    # PLot lables
    plt.yticks(my_range, x2.lbl, fontname = "Sans Serif", fontsize=9)
    plt.xticks(x_ticks, fontsize = 10)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'x', rotation = 0)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 9)
    #plt.title("Times New Roman 18", fontname = "Times New Roman", fontsize=18)
    plt.xlabel('Production Spans', fontname = "Sans Serif", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('DU Material Class', fontname = "Sans Serif", fontsize=12)
    
    # Plot historical events as blocks
    plt.axvspan(350, 400, alpha =0.2, color= "red")
    earthquake = mpatches.Patch(color= "red", alpha=0.2, label = " Beginning of the \n Early Byzantine \n Tectonic Paroxysm")

    plt.axvspan(430, 450, alpha = 0.2, color = "green") 
    recon =  mpatches.Patch(color= "green", alpha=0.2, label = " Beginning of Episcopal Precinct \n and House of Eustolios's \n reconstruction?")

    abandon = plt.axvspan(685, 700, alpha = 0.2, color = "blue", label = " Beginning of \n Kourion's abandoment")

    nero =  plt.axvspan(54, 117, alpha = 0.2, color = "yellow", label = " The Reigns of Nero-Trajan")

    severians = plt.axvspan(145, 211, alpha = 0.2, color = "gray", label = " The Severan Dynasty")
    plt.legend(loc ="lower center", bbox_to_anchor= (0.5, -0.3), ncol = 4, handles = [nero, severians, earthquake, recon, abandon], fontsize =10)

    #save options
    if save_plot == 'Y':
         plt.tight_layout()
         plt.savefig(out_ti + fext, dpi = 600)
    else:
        pass

def CC_GenPlot(df, save_plot, out_ti,  fext, start, stop):
    """
    Parameters:
        * df = dataframe of DU material class
        * TITLE = text plot title
        * out_ti = figure title
        * save _plot = save the plot 'Y' or 'N'
        * fext = output file extension (eg '.png')
        * start = earliest date in data set (round it to the nearest century)
        * stop latest date in the dataset (round it to nearest century)
    Requires: seaborn, matplotlib.pyplot and numpy
    """
    import  matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    import matplotlib.patches as mpatches
    import seaborn as sns
    import numpy as np


    df['lbl'] = df.cxn +'-'+ df.Cat.fillna(df.mcls)

    x2 = df

    my_range = range(1, len(x2.index)+1)

    x_ticks = []
    for i in range(start, stop, 100):
        x_ticks.append(i)

    # Plot style
    if len(x2) > 15:
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    else:
        pass

    if len(x2) > 20:
        plt.yticks(my_range, x2.lbl, fontname = "Sans Serif", fontsize=12)
    else:
       
        plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 11)


    sns.set_style("white", rc= {"xtick.bottom": True, "ytick.left": True,})
    sns.set_context("paper", font_scale = 0.9)
    plt.hlines(y=my_range, xmin=x2['date3'], xmax=x2['date4'], color='black', alpha= 1)
    plt.scatter(x2['date3'], my_range, color='black', alpha= 1, label='date3', s = 11)


    # PLot lables
    plt.yticks(my_range, x2.lbl, fontname = "Sans Serif", fontsize=9)
    plt.xticks(x_ticks, fontsize = 10)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'x', rotation = 0)
    plt.tick_params(axis = 'y', rotation = 0, labelsize = 9)
    #plt.title("Times New Roman 18", fontname = "Times New Roman", fontsize=18)
    plt.xlabel('Production Spans', fontname = "Sans Serif", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('CC Material Class', fontname = "Sans Serif", fontsize=12)
    
    # Plot historical events as blocks
    #plt.axvspan(350, 400, alpha =0.2, color= "red")

    #abandon = plt.axvspan(685, 700, alpha = 0.2, color = "blue", label = " Beginning of \n Kourion's abandoment")

    #nero =  plt.axvspan(54, 117, alpha = 0.2, color = "yellow", label = " The Reigns of Nero-Trajan")

    #severians = plt.axvspan(145, 211, alpha = 0.2, color = "gray", label = " The Severian Dynasty")
    #plt.legend(loc ="lower center", bbox_to_anchor= (0.5, -0.3), ncol = 4, handles = [nero, severians, earthquake, recon, abandon], fontsize =10)

    #save options
    if save_plot == 'Y':
         plt.tight_layout()
         plt.savefig(out_ti + fext, dpi = 600)
    else:
        pass

Introduction¶

The shifts between commemorative and industrial space loom large in the Amathous Gate Cemeterys biography. Arguably, it is one of the defining characteristics of the Late Roman incarnation of the cemetery. While Areas A, B, and E follow a similar trajectory, the cyclical character of these shifts produced both broad and localized outcomes in these areas. Chapter 9 explores these outcomes and aims to disentangle and identify their stratigraphic signatures. Like Chapter 7, the discussion and analyses presented in this notebook leverage the techniques laid out in Vol. 1's Chapter 3.

The TA01 Area: TA01, TrA02, TrA07, and TrA08¶

KAGC personnel identified TA01 while excavating TrA02 during the 1998 field season. The discovery of TA01, and a blank tomb (FA10) immediately to its south, suggested that the area around TrA02 had high potential for containing additional cist tombs. As a result, during the 1999 field season, KAGC team members expanded their investigations around TrA02s south and east, with TrA08, and to its west, with TrA07 (Fig. 9.1; Fig. 9.9). Cumulatively, these trenches cover an area of about 60 m2, or approximately 25% of Area As total excavated area. Whi|le these excavations did not uncover additional cist tombs, they did identify several contexts from these trenches that are groupable into three discrete DUs: A014, A015, A017 (Table 9.1). Perhaps the most interesting deposit from around TA01 is the dark stain feature, FA04, which KAGC team members recorded during their excavation of TrA08s Context 004. For the present purpose, we may note that over 200 glass shards, with some deformed by prolonged heat exposure, were recovered from the comparatively small area that FA04 occupied in TrA08. We may also note that the DUs surrounding TA01 differed in their sediment and assemblage compositions from DU A001 from TrA03 and TrA05 as well as DUs A002, A003, and A013 which are associated with the kiln complex (Vol.1's Chapter 10.3) further to the east.

DUs:

  • A501
  • A801
  • A014
  • A015
  • A017
  • FA04

DUS A501¶

KAGC personnel identified one context (Context 005 in Trench TrA02s stratigraphic sequence) within TA01. As the only layer from within TA01, it is also the only Contributing Context (CC) associated with Depositional Unit A501 (DU A501). DU A501s sediment consisted of c. 0.400.45 m of very loose yellowish-brown to brownish-gray sandy silt. Although DU A501s sediment was similar to DU A801s, it lacked the clast and irregular limestone spall inclusions that characterize the latter. The excavators also noted extensive root intrusions and a moderate number of snail shells in the tombs northern and western sectors. DU A501 abutted all of Tomb TA01s interior walls and directly overlaid its floor. The DUs interfaces with these interior surfaces were all sharply defined. Before excavating within Tomb TA01, KAGC team members also noted that numerous human bones were resting on and protruding through DU A501s upper interface. However, most of the human bone was concentrated within c. 0.20 m of the tombs floor. The human remains consisted of c. 501 bone and bone fragments clustered in and around the tombs northwestern sector. These fragments are attributable to an MNI (Minimum Number of Individuals) of four, including one adult male (2357 years), two females (2731 and 1545 years) (Volume 2, Chapter 2, Table 2.5) and one indeterminate individual.

DU A801¶

DU A801 corresponds to TrA02s Context 003. Its sediment consisted of loose, light grayish-brown sandy silt with abundant irregular limestone spall and clast fragment inclusions. It filled the faceted slot and platform that contained Tomb TA01, totally overlaying the tomb, and abutted against the faceted slots faces. DU A801s interface with TA01 and the surrounding bedrock was sharply defined. DU A801 is very similar to DUs A017 and A501s sediment.

DU A014¶

DU A014 consists of three Contributing Contexts (CC): Trench TrA02s Context 001, Trench TrA07s Context 001, and Trench TrA08s Context 001. DU A014s sediment consisted of a grayish-brown to light-brown silty sand with graded compaction. The sediment contained numerous comparatively small angular limestone inclusions and numerous rootlets but few artifacts. DU A014 completely overlaid DU A015 in Trenches TrA07 and TrA08. However, in Trench TrA02s eastern sector, DU A014 was exceptionally shallow (< 0.10 m) and it overlaid worked bedrock, an incomplete cist tomb (FA10), and DU A015. DU A014 also abutted against the bedrock spur wall. The interface between DU A014 and the spur wall and underlying bedrock, including FA10, was sharply defined; the interface between DUs A014 and A015 was clearly defined (transitional zone: 2.56.0 cm).

DU A015¶

DU A015 consists of three Contributing Contexts (CC): Trench TrA02s Context 002, Trench TrA07s Context 002, and Trench TrA08s Context 002. DU A015s sediment consisted of pale brown sandy silt with graded compaction. The excavators noted that the sediment gradually transitioned horizontally into a dark brown sandy silt with graded compaction in Trenches TrA07 and TrA08. They also noted a substantial increase in fist-sized rubble inclusions and artifact frequencies in TrA07 and TrA08 but not in TrA02. DU A015 overlaid worked bedrock in Trench TrA02 and DU A017 in TrA07 and TrA08. DU A015 also abutted against the bedrock spur wall. DU A015s interface with the underlying bedrock and the spur wall was sharply defined; its interface with DU A017 was clearly defined (transitional zone: 2.56.0 cm).

DU A017¶

DU A017 consists of two Contributing Contexts (CC): Trench TrA07s and Trench TrA08s Contexts 003 and 004, respectively. DU A017s sediment consisted of a dark brown silty sandy with graded compaction. The excavators noted a sharp decrease in artifact frequencies and a rise in fist-sized rubble and angular limestone inclusions. DU A017 overlaid worked bedrock in both trenches and FA04 in TrA08; it also abutted against the spur wall. DU A017s interface with the spur wall and the underlying worked bedrock was sharply defined, though its interface with FA04 was diffuse and poorly defined.

FA04¶

FA04 corresponds to Trench TrA08s Context 005. FA04, a stain, consisted of a discrete ashy area of dark grayish-brown to grayish-brown silty sediment. This stain covered an area of c. 100 x 100 x 3.5 cm was distinct from DU A017s sediment, which surrounded it, in Trench TrA08s southwestern sector. FA04 directly overlaid worked bedrock.

Area B¶

Area B is located between Areas A and C and is delineated by (1) the modern road leading to the Acropolis, which defines Area Bs southern limit, and (2) the comparatively shallow U shaped bay formed by the quarried-out remains of chamber tombs (Chapter 6.2). As mentioned in Chapter 3, Area B is c. 42 m long (eastwest) by 17 m wide (northsouth) and covers an area of c. 575 m2. During the 1996 1998 field seasons, KAGC personnel sampled c. 87% (n = 500.3 m2) of Area B with a grid of standard-sized trenches (i.e. 5 x 5 m) (see Fig. 9.15 for a map, Fig. 5.9 for a photograph)

Here we may also note that nearly all the sediment in the trenches from Area Bs southern sector contained modern material which in some cases was recovered very close to the underlying bedrock surface; these deposits are all Contributing Contexts (CCs) to DU B901 (Chapter 10.5). While the bulldozer truncated most of the sediment in Area Bs eastern quadrant, several trenches were free from modern material; these deposits are all CCs to DU B002 (Fig. 9.21).

Area Bs most important component is the 21 cist tombs the project excavated between 1995 and 1998. Based on an analysis of their centroids, well over half of the tombs fall within one standard deviation from the groups mean center (Fig. 9.15; Table 9.3). The cist tombs are, on average, located 2.50 m from their nearest neighbor. This value, which is slightly larger than the expected random mean distance of 2.21 m, suggests the tombs have a dispersed distribution pattern.

DUs:

  • BDS-1/B501
  • B502
  • B503

BDS-1¶

Area Bs Depositional Sequence 1 (BDS-1) combines DU B002, trench layers without modern artifacts, and DU B501, the upper layer in nearly every cist tomb. Its DU B002 and DU B501 components provide 10 and 20 Contributing Contexts, respectively. The sediment from both components consisted primarily of a semi-compact grayish-brown sandy silt. While angular and rounded rubble and tomb lid fragments were less common in DU B002, they were a significant inclusion type in DU B501 (e.g., TB18). In some cases (e.g., Tomb TB01), tomb lid fragments extended into the underlying sediment (i.e., DUs B502 and B503). Because the construction of the theater road in the late 1980s had truncated BDS-1s DU B002 component, its sediment was relatively shallow (Chapter 3). The interface between BDS-1s DU B002 component and the underlying worked bedrock was sharply defined. It also partially or entirely overlaid several features in Trenches TrB0308 and Trench TrB13. These include blank tombs and libation pipe sockets. In Trench TrB09 (below), BDS-1 overlaid that trenchs Context 003 and abutted against FB19, a mud-bonded wall segment, and their interfaces were clearly defined. BDS-1s DU B501 component varied in thickness (i.e., 0.05 - 020 m). In six cist tombs (e.g., TB03), BDS-1s DU B501 component was the only identifiable layer, filling the tombs completely. Its interface with the tomb floors was sharply defined. In the remaining cases, it either overlaid DU B502 or DU B503; its interface with these DUs was either clearly or sharply defined.

DU B502¶

Nine Contributing Contexts (CC) comprise DU B502. When it is present, DU B502 corresponds to the middle layer in a given cist tomb. Its sediment consists of a semi-compact mottled grayish-brown sandy silt with varying amounts of rubble and tomb lid fragment inclusions. In every occurrence of DU B502, it overlaid DU B503, and in most cases, their interface was either sharply or clearly defined.

In [112]:
b502 = co.Context(KAGC_FUN.DU_Select(df, KAGC_DUS.B502, 'B502'), -24)

DU B503¶

Fourteen Contributing Contexts (CC) comprise DU B503. When it is present, DU B503 corresponds to the lowest layer within a given cist tomb. Its sediment consists of loose to semi-compact comparatively thin (c. 0.25 m) deposits of either a yellowish silty sand or a yellowish-brown moist silty sand. Overall, DU B503 had appreciably fewer rubble and tomb lid fragment inclusions than DUs B502 and B501. Except for Tomb TB10, each of DU B503s Contributing Contexts overlaid their respective tombs floor, and in nearly every case, this interface was sharply defined.

In [134]:
b503 = co.Context(KAGC_FUN.DU_Select(df, KAGC_DUS.B503, 'B503'), -24)

Area B Case studies¶

he case studies presented in this section illustrate the primary stratigraphic sequences from Area Bs cist tombs. Tomb TB03 represents several tombs that contain only one DU, BDS-1s DU B501 component. Similarly, Tomb TB09 provides an excellent representative example of cist tombs where BDS-1s DU B501 component directly overlies DU B503. TB18 provides a clear example of the standard three deposit stratigraphic sequence, BDS-1s DU B501 component, DU B502, and B503, from Area Bs cist tombs. Besides providing a clear example of the standard three-deposit sequence, TB10 also provides a unique example of a heavily modified/repaired cist tomb floor. Its false floor has no parallels within the KAGC study area. TB08 has the most complex stratigraphic sequence out of the cist tombs the project excavated. It also provides evidence of episodic infilling and historical disturbance not recorded in the stratigraphic sequences from Area Bs other cist tombs. The case studies also include one trench, Trench TrB09, which has a comparatively complex deposit sequence that includes DUs B901 and B002/BDS-1, an unaffiliated context, and two features (FB19 & FB17). In Chapter 10, we discuss Trench TrB15, the case study for DU B901.

TB03¶

Tomb TB03 (max. L: 1.77 m; max. W: 0.76 m; D: 0.190.35 m; orientation: EW; headrest: W; DU B501; BDS-1; MNI: 1) contained one context, 001, which is a Contributing Context to DU B501. The excavators also noted that this tomb lacks framing drainage channels and is noticeably shallow compared to neighboring Tombs TB01, TB04, and TB09 and has a damaged headrest. Except for a tibia fragment, the human bone assemblage consists mostly of unidentifiable fragments attributable to one indeterminate individual (Volume 2, Chapter 2).

TB08¶

Tomb TB08 (max. length: 1.88 m; max. width: 0.82 m; center depth: 0.88 m; orientation: NS; headrest: N; DUs: B501B507; MNI: 1) is located in TrB08 and TrB09. KAGC team members identified eight contexts from this tomb. Tomb TB08 also provides an excellent example of the rock-cut channels and libation pipe sockets often associated with cist tombs in the KAGC study area. Its stratigraphic sequence is also the most complex recorded for a cist tomb in the study area (Fig. 9.24). The most interesting aspect of TB08s stratigraphic sequence is that it provides reasonable evidence for historic tomb disturbances and in-filling in Area B after its use as a commemorative space. Nearly all the human bone came from Context 007, a CC to DU B503, and included articulated leg bones.

TB09¶

Tomb TB09 (max. L: 2.03 m; max. width: 0.85 m; D: 0.610.78 m; orientation: EW; headrest: W; DU: B501, B503; MNI: 1) contained two contexts, 001 and 002, which are Contributing Contexts to DUs B501 and B503 respectively. The excavators noted that more significant pieces of rubble and lid fragments occupied the tombs western sector. They also noted that a large root had damaged a substantial portion of the tombs northern sector.

TrB09¶

Trench TrB09s (5 x 5 m, 25 m2; datum: NW; DUs B901, B002/ BDS-1; Features: FB17, FB19) stratigraphy is among the more complex from Area Bs eastern sector. It contained three contexts, 001, 002, and 003, and a feature, FB19. Contexts 001 and 002 are Contributing Contexts (CC) to DUs B901 and BDS-1s DU B002 component, respectively; Context 003 is unaffiliated.

Area E¶

Except for the topographic survey, the projects activities in Areas C, D, E, and F were limited in scope: KAGC personnel excavated only two tombs, TE20 and TE22, in Area E. Area E is located c. 200 m to Area Bs northeast and is situated on a comparatively flat roughly triangular plateau-like rise of limestone bedrock (Fig. 9.40; see Fig. 5.7 for a map and Fig. 5.12 for a photograph from above). This rise includes and overlooks parts of Areas, C, D, E, and F (Chapter 5.4). The rise is c. 50 m from east to west and 60 m from north to south, and covers an area of c. 0.21 ha. Grass/low scrub interspersed with stretches of exposed bedrock characterizes much of this areas current ground surface.

Like the cist tombs in Area B, rock-cut channels/drains also help define Area Es cist tombs against the quarried surface. TE22 is also equipped with what appears to be a roughly rendered lid stop on its eastern end (below). However, apart from its comparatively flat surface and facets associated with arcosolia tombs along the bedrock ridge that defines most of the rises western boundary, there is considerably less overt evidence for extensive quarry activity in this sector of the cemetery in comparison to Areas A and B.

DUs:

  • E501
  • E502
  • E503

E501¶

DU E501, the uppermost deposit from Tombs TE20 and TE22, has two CCs: Tomb TE20s Context 001 and Tomb TE22s Context 001. DU E501 consisted of comparatively thin (c. 0.100.15 m) loose, very dark brown loamy sediment with abundant rubble inclusions and tomb lid fragments. The excavators also noted extensive root disturbances in both DUs Contributing Contexts. In Tomb TE20s southern sector, the excavators also noted the presence of a large horizontally orientated limestone lid fragment at the interface of that tombs Context 001 and 002 (i.e., DU E502). In its western sector, the excavators noted several large lid fragments. DU E501 overlaid DU E502, and their interfaces were clearly defined (transitional zone: 2.56.0 cm).

E502¶

DU E502, the middle deposit in Tombs TE20 and TE22, has two CCs: Tomb TE20s Context 002 and Tomb TE22s Context 002. DU E502 consisted of a relatively thick (c. 0.28 m) loose to semi- compact brownish-gray silty sand sediment with gravel and fist-sized angular rubble inclusions. In Tomb TE22, the excavators also noted that the westernmost of the two lid fragments first identified in that tombs Context 001 continued through this deposit and into the underlying sediment (i.e., DU E503). There were also large lid fragments in Tomb TE20. Overall, the artifact frequency exhibited a moderate increase in DU E502. DU E502 overlaid B503 in both tombs; their interfaces were clearly defined (transitional zone: 2.56.0 cm).

E503¶

DU E503, the lowest deposit in Tombs TE20 and TE22, has two CCs: Tomb TE20s Context 003 and Tomb TE22s Context 003. Its sediment consisted of a semi-compact light brown sandy silt with moderate angular rubble inclusions and tomb lid fragments. The excavators noted that in Tomb TE20, this sediment was comparatively moist. DU E503 overlaid the tombs floors, and their interfaces were sharply defined.

In [223]:
